            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">DC.IX.R6</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">His story</span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Calibri,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Traddles's \"story\" is another of the narratives provided to stand alongside and against David's own \"personal history\" (see <em>DC.III.R4</em>). Traddles's story of diligence and faithfulness offers an interesting counterpoint both to the carelessness of Steerforth (see <em>DC.IX.R1</em>), and to David himself, particularly after the lengthy description of his infatuation with Dora in chapter 26. Indeed, Traddles's great care for his sparse &ldquo;furnishing,&rdquo; included just below on the Working Note, signifies his simplicity and patience, as does his repeated adage, &rdquo;wait and hope!&rdquo; (DC 413). Just like his &ldquo;little round table with the marble top,&rdquo; Traddles is &ldquo;firm as a rock,&rdquo; and his determined nature might remind the reader of Aunt Betsey&rsquo;s hopes for David in No. VII: that he will be a &ldquo;fine firm fellow, with a will of [his] own&rdquo; (DC 283). </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"
